article.description:
Deanna Nolan scored 22 points and
Kara Braxton added a double-double as the Detroit Shock routed the
Chicago Sky 82-48 on Thursday night.
article.headline: Shock rout Sky, inch closer to clinching East's No. 2 seed
article.linkText: Shock rip Sky, inch closer to clinching East's No. 2 seed
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Deanna Nolan scored 22 points and
Kara Braxton added a double-double as the Detroit Shock routed the
Chicago Sky 82-48 on Thursday night.

	   Detroit cruised to the easy victory despite losing All-Star
Cheryl Ford to a sprained left hand midway through the first
quarter. Ford, who is listed as day-to-day, was the only Shock
player that did not score.

	   "Obviously, we match up well with them, but we didn't
understand their game plan," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said of
the Sky's slow-down game. "On offense, they waited until there
were eight seconds left on the shot clock, then tried to go
one-on-one, which doesn't work against us. On defense, they just
sat in a passive zone."

	   Chicago lost its 14th straight road game after winning their
franchise opener 83-82 at Charlotte on May 20.

	   "We're just trying to do things to level the playing field a
little bit," Sky coach Dave Cowens said. "I wanted to limit their
possessions, because they are a better team, man for man. It worked
for a while, but we lost focus. When you lose focus, there's not
much else you can do."

	   Braxton had 13 points and 12 rebounds while filling in for Ford.
The Shock bench outscored Chicago's reserves 24-2 in the first
three quarters.

	   Candice Dupree led the Sky with 12 points.

	   "We were trying to run a certain offense against them and I
think we tried to use it a little too long," Dupree said.

	   The Shock can clinch the Eastern Conference's second seed on
Friday, giving them homecourt advantage in the first round, with a
win in Washington or an Indiana loss to Connecticut.

	   Detroit used a 31-5 second period to put the game away.

	   Nolan thought about trying to dunk when she had a breakaway with
Detroit up 29 late in the third quarter. She decided at the last
second not to try one in a regular-season game.

	   "I was going to, but I know how Bill gets about things like
that," said Nolan, who missed dunk attempts in each of the last
two All-Star games. "So I just laid it in."

	   Chicago missed its first nine shots of the period, including a
blown fast-break layup by Stacey Dales. Bernadette Ngoyisa, though,
ruined Detroit's shutout hopes with a short jumper with 1:05 left
in the period.

	   The Shock, which scored the first 25 points of the period, went
into halftime with a 50-21 lead.

	   Shock coach Bill Laimbeer took advantage of the score to rest
his starters for most of the second half. Nolan led the team with
just 26 minutes.

	   Detroit set a franchise record with 11 3-pointers.
